Transactions
 Transactions = safe execution of multiple queries
This is used in banking, payments, orders, etc.
🧠 What is a Transaction?
👉 A transaction = group of SQL operations executed together
👉 Either:
✅ All succeed
❌ Or all fail

💡 Real-Life Example (Best Way to Understand)
👉 Bank transfer:
Deduct ₹100 from Account A
Add ₹100 to Account B
If one fails → money should NOT disappear ❌
👉 That’s why we use transactions

🔄 Basic Syntax
BEGIN;
UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance - 100 WHERE id = 1;
UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance + 100 WHERE id = 2;
COMMIT;

🧠 Key Commands
1 BEGIN / START TRANSACTION
👉 Starts transaction
BEGIN;

2 COMMIT
👉 Save changes permanently ✅
COMMIT;

3 ROLLBACK
👉 Undo all changes ❌
ROLLBACK;

🔥 Example with Error
BEGIN;
UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance - 100 WHERE id = 1;
-- Error happens here
ROLLBACK;
👉 Result:
No money deducted
System stays safe 👍

🧠 ACID Properties (Very Important 🔥🔥)
Transactions follow ACID rules

🔹 A – Atomicity
👉 “All or nothing”

🔹 C – Consistency
👉 Data remains correct

🔹 I – Isolation
👉 Transactions don’t disturb each other

🔹 D – Durability
👉 Once committed → data is saved forever

🔥 Isolation Levels (Interview Level)
👉 Control how transactions interact
READ UNCOMMITTED
READ COMMITTED
REPEATABLE READ
SERIALIZABLE
👉 Higher level = more safety but slower

⚠️ Common Problems (Important)

🔹 Dirty Read
👉 Reading uncommitted data

🔹 Non-repeatable Read
👉 Data changes during transaction

🔹 Phantom Read
👉 New rows appear during transaction

